{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566699"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:46:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:46:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18870"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18870"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.08,0.04,0.04,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11603"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112479"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11603"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18870"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94510"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"2253"},{"type":"tags","id":"5788"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27309"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46157"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112479"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by ambulance after being found unconscious. On arrival, his pulse rate is 58/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 6/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. His oxygen saturation improves to 96% with supplemental oxygen via nasal cannula. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears drowsy with pinpoint pupils. Cardiorespiratory examination is otherwise unremarkable. An arterial blood gas was taken, with reference ranges as below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaCO2 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaO2 mmHg (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following arterial blood gas findings would be most likely?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["pH 7.25, PaCO2 40, HCO3 16, PaO2 95","pH 7.30, PaCO2 40, HCO3 19, PaO2 90","pH 7.40, PaCO2 35, HCO3 16, PaO2 85","pH 7.45, PaCO2 38, HCO3 24, PaO2 65","pH 7.20, PaCO2 65, HCO3 24, PaO2 70"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of opiate overdose including respiratory depression (respiratory rate 6/min), decreased consciousness, and pinpoint pupils. The key physiological derangement is hypoventilation leading to carbon dioxide retention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.20, PaCO2 65, HCO3 24, PaO2 70\u003C/strong\u003E represents acute respiratory acidosis, the expected finding in opiate-induced respiratory depression. The decreased ventilation leads to CO2 retention (elevated PaCO2), which combines with water to form carbonic acid, lowering blood pH. The normal bicarbonate level indicates this is an acute process without metabolic compensation yet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.25, PaCO2 40, HCO3 16, PaO2 95\u003C/strong\u003E represents metabolic acidosis with low bicarbonate and acidaemia, but normal CO2. This pattern would be seen in conditions like diabetic ketoacidosis or lactic acidosis, not opiate overdose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.30, PaCO2 40, HCO3 19, PaO2 90\u003C/strong\u003E suggests metabolic acidosis with normal CO2 and low bicarbonate, rather than the respiratory acidosis seen in opiate overdose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.40, PaCO2 35, HCO3 16, PaO2 85\u003C/strong\u003E shows compensated metabolic acidosis with normal pH achieved through respiratory compensation (lower CO2), which is not consistent with acute respiratory depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.45, PaCO2 38, HCO3 24, PaO2 65\u003C/strong\u003E shows normal pH and CO2 with isolated hypoxaemia, suggesting a primary gas exchange problem rather than hypoventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of this condition involves addressing both the respiratory depression with naloxone and providing respiratory support as needed. The arterial blood gas changes will normalise as the respiratory rate improves.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Opiate overdose causes respiratory depression leading to respiratory acidosis with elevated PaCO2 and decreased pH.","Compensatory mechanisms take several hours to increase bicarbonate levels in response to respiratory acidosis.","Pure respiratory acidosis is characterised by normal bicarbonate levels in the acute phase."],"references":["Schiller EY, Goyal A, Mechanic OJ. Opioid Overdose. [Updated 2023 Jul 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470415/","Castro D, Patil SM, Zubair M, et al. Arterial Blood Gas. [Updated 2024 Jan 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK536919/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94510"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18870"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94510"},"attributes":{"c